Manual vs Automated Trading

How has the increase in prevelance of Automated Trading Systems (ATS) influenced the futures market?

  • CME transaction data identitifies ATS with the 1028 tag
  • Data available from November 2012 to present
  • We consider data form 2012 to 2016
  • We use gradient plots to highlight the changes between these two periods
  • Graphs are interactive

Trade Participation

Time between order placement and execution

ATS

  • ATS have not yet achieved the presence in futures that they have in FX and equities
  • Percentage of trades executed by ATS will only increase in the future
  • Volume percentage allocated to ATS will increase for all time scales
  • ATS has first pick of the alpha available from new information, manual traders will have to pick what is left on the bones

Value of Manual Traders

  • Ability to trade less liquid and over-the-counter contracts
  • Ability to see market-fundamental disjointness especially in longer dated contracts
  • Ability to react to macro events

Literature

  • Algorithmic trading and Market Dynamics

Grinold’s Fundamental Law of Active Portfolio Management

Law of active portfolio management

  • Performance
  • Skill
  • Breadth

\[ \text{Performance} = \text{Skill} \times \sqrt{\text{Breadth}} \]

Coin Flipping Casino

  • Flip coins in stead of futures
  • The coin is biased - \(P(\text{heads}) = 0.51\)

Betting

Bet \(N\) coins

  • Win: now have \(2 N\) coins
  • Lose: now have 0 coins

Casino

  • 1000 tables
  • 1000 tokens
  • Game runs in parallel

How do you allocate tokens?

Two extremes

  • Bet 1000 tokens on one coin flip
  • Bet 1 token on 1000 coin flips

Expected Return

  • Single bet: \(0.51 \times 1000 + 0.49 \times (-1000) = 20\)

  • Multi bet: \(1000 \times [0.51 + 0.49 \times (-1)] = 20\)

The same expected return

Risk - Probability to lose it all:

  • Single bet: 49%

  • Multi bet: \(0.49 \times 0.49 \times \dots \times 0.49 = 0.49^{1000} \approx 0\)

Risk - Standard Deviation:

  • One token per table

\[ \text{risk} := \text{std}\left\{1,-1,-1,1, \dots, 1 \right\} = 1 \]

  • One 1000 token bet, 999 zero token bets

\[ \begin{align} \text{risk} &:= \text{std}\left\{1000,0,0,0, \dots, 0 \right\} = 31.62 \\ \text{risk} &:= \text{std}\left\{-1000,0,0,0, \dots, 0 \right\} = 31.62 \end{align} \]

Coin Flip Casino - Reward/Risk

  • Just like Sharpe Ratio

  • Single bet: \(\text{SR}_{\text{single}} = \frac{20}{31.62} =0.63\)

  • Multi bet: \(\text{SR}_{\text{multiple}} = \frac{20}{1} =20\)

Coin Flip Casino - Observation

  • \(20 = 0.63 \times \sqrt{1000}\)

  • \(\text{SR}_{\text{multiple}} = \text{SR}_{\text{single}} \times \sqrt{\text{Bets}}\)

  • \(\text{Performance} = \text{Skill} \times \sqrt{\text{Breadth}}\)

Literature

  • The fundamental law of active management - Richard C. Grinold
  • Extending the Fundamental Law of Investment Management - JP Morgan US Equity Quantitative Research

Short Volatility

Bird’s Eye View

  • Capture risk premium driven by consumer and producer hedging
  • Tries to capture premium of implied over realised vols
  • Diversifies by including 16 commodities with dynamic tenure
  • Avoids periods that are not suited to be short vol

Seasonality in Volatility

  • Reduce potential large drawdowns by avoiding high risk periods

Carry

Bird’s Eye View

  • Take advantage of curve shape
  • Contango less steep in further-dated contracts
  • Later dated commodity prices higher than near dated prices
  • Construct portfolio of bear spreads (short near, long deferred)

Minimum Drawdown Carry Strategy

Attribute Description
Commodity Universe 16 Commodities
BCOM weights excluding Brent and Precious Metals
7% Natural Gas
36% Agriculture and Softs
33% Base Metals
5% Gold
11% Lean Hogs
25% Petroleum
Weighting Index of futures construction using BCOM weights
Roll Schedule Natural Gas, Gasoline and heating oil - no summer/winter exposure
Corn, Soybeans, Cotton - no old crop/new crop exposure
Mitigate Brazilian winter weather risk for coffee and sugar
No Brent of Precious Metals time spread exposure
Rebalancing Monthly

Backwardation

Bird’s Eye View

  • Later dated commodity prices lower than near dated prices
  • Indicate shortage of supply vs demand
  • Could lead to higher spot returns
  • Sort all commodities according to signal
  • \(\text{signal} = \frac{F_i - F_{i+12}}{F_{i+12}}\)
  • Positive return expectation for top 10, negative for the remainder

Backwardation F3 Strategy

Attribute Description
Commodity Universe 22 Commodities
Signal Front month to 1 year ahead backwardation
Weighting Sorted according to signal
Top 10 are given positive return expectation and the rest negative
Black-Litterman used to determine weights
-100% exposure to BCOM F3
+100% exposure to Black-Littermand optimised portfolio
Rebalancing Monthly
Tracking Error 6% vs benchmark

Enhancing the strategy

  • Include more commodities, from 22 to 32
  • Theoretical improvement of \(\sqrt{\frac{32}{22}} \approx 1.206\)
  • Include diversification contraints
  • Refine views

Momentum

Bird’s Eye View

  • Statistical evidence of predictability of returns using momentum
  • Commodity return less predictable
  • Commodity volatility significantly predictable
  • If we know what volatility will do we know what price will do
  • Overweight best and underweight worst performing commodities
  • \(\text{signal}=\frac{P_{t} - P_{t - 365}}{P_{t - 365}}\)
  • Positive return expectation for top 10, negative for the remainder

Momentum F3 Strategy

Attribute Description
Commodity Universe 22 Commodities
Signal 12 Month momentum of the corresponding BCOM single commodity index
Weighting Sorted according to signal
Top 10 are given positive return expectation and the rest negative
Black-Litterman used to determine weights
-100% exposure to BCOM F3
+100% exposure to Black-Littermand optimised portfolio
Rebalancing Monthly
Tracking Error 5% vs benchmark

Congestion Rotation

Bird’s Eye View

  • Benchmark indices roll on predefined dates
  • Normally 5th to 9th business day of the month
  • Idea is to trade away from the roll window
  • \(\text{signal}=\frac{P_{\text{close}}}{P_{\text{intraday}}}\)
  • Inflows: more spread selling during the roll
  • Outflows: less spread selling during the roll

Index Flows

Index Rolling

Dynamic Congestion F0 Strategy

Attribute Description
Commodity Universe 25 Commodities
Roll Schedule Monthly and bi-monthly roll schedules on front contracts
Weighting Index of indices construction using equal weights
Rebalancing Monthly
Signal Observe intraday ratio on 5th to last business day of each month
If ratio signals inflow strategy will pre-roll (short spreads)
If ratio signals outflow strategy will post-roll (long spreads)

Congestion Rotator

Attribute Description
Commodity Universe 21 Commodities
Two tenures, F0 and F3. Therefore 42 eligible components
Roll Schedule Long leg rolls between 9th last to 7th last business day of the month
Short leg rolls between 5th last to 9th last business day of the month
Weighting Risk-adjusted return
Capped according to 35/20 diversification rule
Rebalancing Monthly
Signal For each commodity and tenure asses recent congestion performance
Take exposure to commodities and tenors with positive performance
Exclude commodities with negative performance

Pairs

Bird’s Eye View

  • Consider natural pair with sufficient liquidity
  • Bollinger band type strategy
  • Calculate rolling mean and standard deviations
  • Enter trade when ratio exceeds two standard deviation from mean
  • Take profit when ratio is within half a standard deviation from mean
  • Stop loss when ratio moves a further half a standard deviation away from mean

Pairs Example

Pairs Trading Strategy

Attribute Description
Commodity Universe 21 Pairs
Signal Buy/Sell when ratio moves more than 2 standard deviations from mean
Take profit when ratio returns to withing 1/2 standard deviation
Bollinger Band type strategy
Weighting Energy and precious metals equal weighted capped to pair with lowest capacity
Rebalancing Monthly
Stop-loss Ratio moves further 1/2 standard deviation from inception
Exclusions Pairs containing robusta and white sugar - low liquidity

Literature

  • Pairs Trading: Performance of a Relative Value Arbitrage Rule - Gatev et al.
  • Pairs Trading - Vidyamurthy
  • The Application of Pairs Trading to Energy Futures Markets - Kanamura et al.

Trend Following

Bird’s Eye View

  • Trend following is about absolute performance of each commodity
  • Momentum is relative values of some commodites vs others
  • Straddle like behaviour
  • Performs well in extreme markets
  • Signals are monthly and weekly log returns
  • Equal target risk weighted
  • Allocate 40% to wwekly signal
  • Allocate 60% to monthly signal

Trend Following Strategy

Attribute Description
Commodity Universe 27 Commodities
Signal Go long if the commodity is trending up and short if trending down
Front month or F3
Vol-capped at 10% volatility
Weighting Index of indices construction using equal weights
Rebalancing Monthly
Roll Schedule Monthly and bi-monthly roll schedules. Front and F3

Literature

  • Time series momentum - Moskowitz et al.
  • Which trend is your friend - Levine and Pedersen
